<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-180-298  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 180 298.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Journal of Systems Management  March 1989 v40 n3 p28(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Electronic authorization - the next wave in automation.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Lewis, Barry.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Despite significant advances in reducing or eliminating the amountof paper in day-to-day lives, strong forces continue to promotethe use of paper.andP;  One major force is the demand that a signature,written in ink on paper, be provided as proof that something hasbeen approved, authorized or authenticated.andP;  Electronicauthorization (EA) is beginning to be accepted in place of thiswritten signature.andP;  Another major area is access to data.andP;  EA canmeet the needs of users who want fast access to data and auditorsand management who want a secure system.andP;  An EA system must beefficient, simple to maintain, flexible, reliable, be able togenerate reports and to archive collected audit data.andP;  The futurewill bring full automation of most, if not all, authorizationprocesses as EA systems become commonplace.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Signature VerificationOffice AutomationAccess Controls.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>